 at the dynamics of environmental gentrification, documenting the symbiosis between eco-friendly initiatives and high-end redevelopment and its impact on out-of-the-way, non-gentrifying neighborhoods. At the same time, she highlights the valiant efforts of local environmental justice activists who work across racial, economic, and political divides to challenge sustainability’s false promises and create truly viable communities.The Sustainability Myth is a cautionary, eye-opening tale, taking a hard—but ultimately hopeful—look at environmental justice activism and the politics of sustainability.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningxEnvironmental aspects. 0aEnvironmental justice. 0aGentrification. 0aSustainable urban development. 0aUrban ecology (Sociology) 0aUrban ecology (Sociology). 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aActivist Overwhelm.  aActivist OverwhelmStaten Island Politics.  aBrown Gentrification.  aBrownfield Programs.  aCity Planning.  aCity Zoning.  aCivic Engagement.  aCommunity Development.  aEnvironmental Activism.  aEnvironmental Crisis.  aEnvironmental Gentrification.  aEnvironmental Protections.  aEnvironmental Sustainability.  aGeographic Politics.  aGreen Gentrification.  aIndustrial Business.  aIndustrial Gentrification.  aIndustrialization.  aUrban Nature.  aUrban Sustainability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070480808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Medicine and Life Sciences 2020z9783110704600oZDB-23